            <h3>parent</h3>
            <p>parent property refers to the DisplayObject's parent DisplayObjectContainer. You can use multiple parents to go back to the ancestor.</p>

            <h5>Example</h5>
            <p><pre>const {Shape} = next2d.display;
const shape = new Shape();
this.addChild(shape);
console.log(shape.parent === this);</pre></p>

            <h3>root</h3>
            <p>root property refers to the main timeline containing the DisplayObject. There are the following exceptions.
              <ul>
                <li>A Stage refers to itself.</li>
                <li>An off-list DisplayObject returns null.</li>
              </ul>
            </p>

            <p><pre>const {Sprite} = next2d.display;
const sprite = new Sprite();
console.log(sprite.root); // null
this.addChild(sprite);
console.log(sprite.root === this.root);</pre></p>

            <p><a class="float-end read-more" href="8.html">${{ main.next-chapter }}$</a></p>
          </div>
        </div>
